@node MapWindow "TRC User's Guide | Reference | Windows | Map"
@toc  Windows
@{u}@{b}The Map Window@{ub}@{uu}

The Map Window displays the game map - it @{b}is@{ub} the game map.  The window
contains a fixed sized bitmap rendition of The Russian Campaign map.  The Map
Window may be moved and sized.  Scrolling is done by proportional scroll bars
in the right and bottom borders.  The window is open at all times.

In the Map Window the game units are moved using the mouse as described in
the @{"Mouse Input" link Mouse} section.

@endnode


@remark-----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node CounterMixWindows "TRC User's Guide | Reference | Windows | Counter Mix"
@toc  Windows
@{u}@{b}Counter Mix Windows@{ub}@{uu}

There are two counter mix windows:  a Russian Counter Mix and a German
Counter Mix.  Counter Mix windows represent the supply of game counters
neatly stacked by type, somewhere off-board.  They look like horizontally
arranged rows of units, one of each type.  Underneath each unit is a number
indicating the quantity of that unit type remaining in the counter mix.
(In some games, the quantity of units provided in the counter mix is
significant.  In the Russian Campaign it isn't because the Order-of-Battle
specifies precisely what units become available when.  Thus, the quantities
for all unit types start out a completely arbitrary 99. i.e. Lots).

Counter Mix windows are fixed sized.  They are opened via menu choice 
View|Open <side> Counter Mix.  They are "modeless", and may be left
displayed if the player can afford the screen real estate.

Counters are moved between Map and Counter Mix windows using the mouse as
described in the Mouse Input section.  When a new unit is deployed it is
moved from the counter mix to the map.  When a unit is destroyed, it is moved
from the map to the counter mix.

Note that no Replacement Pool areas have been explicitly provided on the map.
A section of the Black or Baltic seas should serve admirably well.

@endnode


